\section{ML/DL in phage virology}\label{sec:phage_virology}

\subsection{Data types}

Organize by modality and typical dataset structure:

- Genomic and metagenomic sequences  
  - Viral contigs and complete genomes from isolates and metagenomes; often paired with host genomes or at least host taxonomic labels. [pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/40359589/)
  - Large unlabeled sequence corpora used for self‑supervised representation learning or protein language models. [institut-vision](https://www.institut-vision.org/en/news/machine-learning-meets-microbiology-advance-personalized-phage-therapy)

- Omics and systems data  
  - Transcriptomics, proteomics and metabolomics time courses across infection cycles; sometimes combined with bacterial pan-genome and defense systems. [research.kuleuven](https://research.kuleuven.be/portal/en/project/3E210935)

- Experimental phenotype data  
  - High‑throughput phage × host infectivity matrices, digital phagograms, and time‑kill curves for different MOIs and conditions. [biblio.ugent](https://biblio.ugent.be/publication/8733425)

\subsection{Target resolution}

- Host range and host species/strain from phage genome or specific genes. [pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12579225/)
- Lifestyle (lytic vs temperate), virulence factors, and presence of AMR or lysogeny‑related genes. [theseus](https://www.theseus.fi/bitstream/10024/889389/2/Uddin_MdKarim.pdf)
- Multi‑stage infection outcome: adsorption probability, infection success, replication yield, and lysis timing (“layered” or multi‑task targets). [research.kuleuven](https://research.kuleuven.be/portal/en/project/3E210935)
- Phage cocktail performance: predicted success of combinations against a bacterial community, including synergy/antagonism. [youtube](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1ORg_lzV61I)

\subsection{Methodology and model types}

- Classical ML  
  - Random forests, gradient boosting, SVMs on k‑mer features, gene presence/absence matrices, or CRISPR/receptor feature sets. [pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12579225/)

- Deep learning  
  - CNNs and transformers on raw nucleotide or amino‑acid sequences for classification and host prediction. [pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/40359589/)
  - Protein language models (e.g. BERT‑like) trained on millions of phage proteins, used for downstream tasks such as host prediction, lifestyle, or functional annotation. [institut-vision](https://www.institut-vision.org/en/news/machine-learning-meets-microbiology-advance-personalized-phage-therapy)
  - Graph‑based models using bipartite host–phage networks or gene co‑occurrence networks to infer missing edges (new interactions). [research.kuleuven](https://research.kuleuven.be/portal/en/project/3E210935)

- Experimental/ML integration  
  - Active learning for designing new host‑range assays or refining phage cocktails based on model uncertainty. [institut-vision](https://www.institut-vision.org/en/news/machine-learning-meets-microbiology-advance-personalized-phage-therapy)
  - Interpretable multilayer models aligned with biological steps (receptors, defense systems, metabolic hijacking), making phage systems a test bed for mechanistic ML. [biblio.ugent](https://biblio.ugent.be/publication/8733425)

\subsection{Strengths and limitations specific to phages}

- Strengths: dense infectivity matrices, well‑defined targets (binary/graded infection), short genomes, and ease of experimental validation. [biblio.ugent](https://biblio.ugent.be/publication/8733425)
- Limitations: ecological complexity in vivo, bias toward culturable hosts, and difficulty transferring models built on a few species to diverse microbiomes. [pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/40359589/)